of it as no more than a piece of rhetorical playfulness, at times challenging, though useful for supplying a memorable sententious note or for performing a pirouette of syntax and thought. Going beyond traditional rhetoric, this volume is concerned with the possibility of using the figure of chiasmus to model a broad array of phenomena, from human relations to artistic creation. In the process, it provides the first book-length study not of chiasmus, the rhetorical figure, but of chiastic thought. The contributors are concerned with chiastic inversion and its place in social interactions, cultural creation, and more generally human thought and experience.They explore from a variety of angles what the unsettling logic of chiasmus (from the Greek meaning “cross-wise”), has to tell us about the world, human relations, cultural patterns, psychology, and artistic and poetic creation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aChiasmus. 0aInterpersonal relations and culture. 0aRhetoricxSocial aspects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh1 aBollig, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHariman, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, E. Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Anthony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSalazar, Philippe-Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrecker, Ivo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas-Fogiel, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTyler, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUsher, Phillip John, e